@remark *********************************************************************

@node IntroductionNode "ScreenMenuEd: Introduction"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Introduction@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

ScreenMenuEd lets you create, edit and test custom menu definitions
that you can later attach to a public screen using @{"ScreenMaster" link "ScreenMaster.guide/Main"}, or
directly via ARexx and @{"ScreenBacker" link "ScreenBacker.guide/Main"}.@{par}

You can define a set of menus with items that launch your favourite
commands, in a manner similar to the Workbench Tools menu. If you wish
you can tailor the environment that these commands are launched in to
suit your requirements, including current directory, standard output,
stack and priority.@{par}

Don't forget, however, that ScreenBacker itself automatically provides
one menu with a suite of useful public screen management functions -
see the @{"Standard Menu" link "ScreenBacker.guide/StdMenuNode"} section of ScreenBacker's guide for details. You
will also find the @{"technical specification" link "ScreenBacker.guide/MenuDefNode"} of menu definition files in
that guide.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node RequirementsNode "ScreenMenuEd: Requirements"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Requirements@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

ScreenMenuEd requires:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} AmigaOS 2.04 / Kickstart V37 or higher.@{line}
@{lindent 0}

The BGUI version requires:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} bgui.library V38 or higher. @{i}(windows, gadgets, etc)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

The MUI version requires:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} MUI V2.3 or higher. @{i}(windows, gadgets, etc)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

The following disk-based Commodore library is required, but is part of
AmigaOS 2.04 (and later releases) anyway:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} asl.library V37 or higher. @{i}(requesters)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

The following disk-based libraries are optional, but their absence
will limit the functionality of ScreenMenuEd:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} locale.library V38 or higher. @{i}(localization)@{ui}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} diskfont.library V36 or higher. @{i}(custom font support)@{ui}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} amigaguide.library V33 or higher. @{i}(on-line help)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node UsingNode "ScreenMenuEd: Using the Program"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Using the Program@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

To start ScreenMenuEd, simply double click on its icon from Workbench,
or type its name into a Shell (assuming it's in your Shell's search
path). You can also specify an initial menu definition file to load on
the command line, or by standard shift-selection of a project icon
from the Workbench.@{par}

For further information, consult one of the sections below:

@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} @{"ScreenMenuEd's Window" link MenuEdWinNode}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} @{"ScreenMenuEd's Menu" link MenuEdMenuNode}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} @{"Edit Menu Definition Window" link EditWinNode}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} @{"Menu Definition Rules" link MenuRulesNode}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node MenuEdWinNode "ScreenMenuEd: ScreenMenuEd's Window"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}ScreenMenuEd's Window@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=====================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Most of ScreenMenuEd's window is occupied by a listview in which the
currently defined menus and items are shown. The labels of the menus
and items run down the left of the list, with menus in a highlight
colour. If an item has a shortcut key defined, this is displayed on
the right hand side.@{par}

A special kind of item, @{i}a separator bar@{ui}, is shown as a horizontal
line. You can insert these separator bars into your menu definitions
in order to separate logically distinct sets of items.@{par}

At the bottom of the window lie nine button gadgets:@{par}


@{fg shine}Insert...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}---------@{fg text}@{line}
Inserts a new menu or item into the list, before the current one. The
@{"Edit Menu Definition" link EditWinNode} window opens, to let you set the attributes of
the new menu or item.@{par}


@{fg shine}Edit...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{line}
Edits the current menu or item in the list. The @{"Edit Menu Definition" link EditWinNode}
window opens, to let you edit the attributes of the menu or item.@{par}


@{fg shine}Remove@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}------@{fg text}@{line}
Removes the current menu or item completely.@{par}


@{fg shine}Up@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}--@{fg text}@{line}
Moves the current menu or item up one place.@{par}


@{fg shine}Down@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{line}
Moves the current menu or item down one place.@{par}


@{fg shine}Test@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{line}
Press this button to test your menu definition. ScreenMenuEd will
check it over (see @{"Menu Definition Rules" link MenuRulesNode}) and if it's okay, open a new
window with your custom menu attached. If you activate this window,
you can view and test all your menu items, making sure they perform as
desired. When you're done, close the window, or select "End Test" from
the Project menu.@{par}


@{fg shine}Open...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{line}
Opens a file requester, for you to choose a menu definition file to
load. If the current menu definition has been edited but not saved,
you will be asked for confirmation first.@{par}


@{fg shine}Save@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{line}
Saves the current menu definition with the current filename. If the
definition has not yet been named, a file requester will open to let
you choose one.@{par}


@{fg shine}Quit@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{line}
Quits ScreenMenuEd. If the current menu definition has been edited but
not saved, you will be asked for confirmation first.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node MenuEdMenuNode "ScreenMenuEd: ScreenMenuEd's Menu"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}ScreenMenuEd's Menu@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

ScreenMenuEd has just one menu, titled "Project", which contains the
following items:@{par}


@{fg shine}New@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}---@{fg text}@{line}
Clears the current list of menus and items completely, to let you
start a new menu definition. If the current menu definition has been
edited but not saved, you will be asked for confirmation first.@{par}


@{fg shine}Open...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{line}
Opens a file requester, for you to choose a menu definition file to
load. If the current menu definition has been edited but not saved,
you will be asked for confirmation first.@{par}


@{fg shine}Edit...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{line}
Edits the current menu or item in the list. The @{"Edit Menu Definition" link EditWinNode}
window opens, to let you edit the attributes of the menu or item.@{par}


@{fg shine}Test...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{line}
Select this item to test your menu definition. ScreenMenuEd will
check it over (see @{"Menu Definition Rules" link MenuRulesNode}) and if it's okay, open a new
window with your custom menu attached. If you activate this window,
you can view and test all your menu items, making sure they perform as
desired. When you're done, close the window, or select "End Test" from
the Project menu.@{par}


@{fg shine}Save@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{line}
Saves the current menu definition with the current filename. If the
definition has not yet been named, a file requester will open to let
you choose one.@{par}


@{fg shine}Save As...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----------@{fg text}@{line}
Lets you save the current menu definition under a new filename. A file
requester will open to let you choose the new name.@{par}


@{fg shine}Help...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{line}
Opens ScreenMenuEd's AmigaGuide documentation. If the guide is not in
AmigaGuide's search path, tell ScreenMenuEd where to find it using the
@{"GUIDENAME" link GUIDENAMENode} tooltype.@{par}


@{fg shine}About...@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}--------@{fg text}@{line}
Opens a requester showing information about ScreenMenuEd.@{par}


@{fg shine}Quit@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{line}
Quits ScreenMenuEd. If the current menu definition has been edited but
not saved, you will be asked for confirmation first.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node EditWinNode "ScreenMenuEd: Edit Menu Definition Window"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Edit Menu Definition Window@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===========================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

When you select to edit or insert a menu or item highlighted in
ScreenMenuEd's main window, the Edit Menu Definition window opens. In
this window you will find gadgets that let you set and test the
attributes of that menu or item.@{par}


@{fg shine}Type@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{line}
This cycle gadget selects the type for the entry, from Menu, Item and
Bar (ie. separator bar). The other gadgets in the window will be
appropriately enabled or disabled according to the type selected.@{par}


@{fg shine}Label@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-----@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Menus and Items.@{ui} The Label string gadget lets you define what text
should appear in the menu for this entry. A label is required for
menus and items but is not applicable to separator bars.@{par}


@{fg shine}Key@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}---@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Items only.@{ui} If you wish to give an item a shortcut key, enter the
desired character in the Key gadget. You will then be able to select
this item in the menu by pressing the right Amiga key and this
character. Remember that the AmigaOS does not distinguish between
upper and lower case shortcut keys; shortcuts are generally displayed
in upper case by convention. A shortcut key is optional.@{par}


@{fg shine}Command@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Items only.@{ui} A command is required for each item; this command will be
executed when you select that item in your custom menu. You can either
type the command into the string gadget, or pick it using a file
requester by pressing the button to the right.@{par}

You can embed up to one instance of the formatting specifier "%s" in
the command string. This will, before the command is executed, be
replaced by the name of the public screen that the menu is attached
to. This makes it possible to get programs to open on that public
screen, for example, "MultiView PUBSCREEN %s".@{par}


@{fg shine}Cur.Dir.@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}--------@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Items only.@{ui} If you wish, you can use this string gadget to specify the
desired current directory for the command. You can either type the
directory name in, or select one from a requester by pressing the
button to the right.@{par}


@{fg shine}Output@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}------@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Items only.@{ui} this string attribute is optional; it allows you to
specify a standard output channel for the command. Typically this
would be a console window, but you could specify a file. As with the
command, you can embed up to one instance of the formatting specifier
"%s" in this string, which will be replaced by the name of the public
screen that the menu is attached to.@{par}

If you leave the Output string blank, you will get the default, which
is: "CON:20/20/600/100/ScreenBacker Output/AUTO/CLOSE/WAIT/SCREEN %s".
Notice how "%s" is used to get this console window to open on the
public screen.@{par}


@{fg shine}Stack@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}-----@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Items only.@{ui} Set the stack size in bytes for the command with this
integer gadget. The default is 8000 bytes, which should be fine for
most programs. Be careful when setting this lower, as many programs
crash if they run out of stack space.@{par}


@{fg shine}Priority@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}--------@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Items only.@{ui} Set the task priority for the command with this integer
gadget. This provides a basic method of determining (relatively) how
much CPU attention the program will get when it is run. The default is
0, which is a standard value. Setting a priority higher than 3 is
strongly discouraged and may upset your Amiga.@{par}


@{fg shine}OK@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}--@{fg text}@{line}
When you are done setting the attributes for this menu or item, select
the OK button. ScreenMenuEd will check the values for validity and
close the Edit Menu Definition window if all is well. Otherwise you
will receive an error message and be returned to the window to correct
the problem.@{par}


@{fg shine}Test@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Items only.@{ui} You can test the correct operation of an item by selecting
the Test button. This launches the command you have specified with the
current directory, output, stack and priority attributes currently set
in the window. The Edit Menu Definition window will stay open.@{par}


@{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text}@{line}
@{fg shine}------@{fg text}@{line}
Select this button to discard any changes you may have made to the
current menu or item and close the Edit Menu Definition window.@{par}


@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node MenuRulesNode "ScreenMenuEd: Menu Definition Rules"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Menu Definition Rules@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=====================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

1. The first entry in a menu definition must be a menu.@{par}

2. The last entry in a menu definition must be an item.@{par}

3. A separator bar must be preceeded and followed by an item. This
means you cannot have a separator bar as the first, or last, entry in
a menu. There would be no point in this anyway.@{par}

4. Every menu and item must have a label.@{par}

5. Every item must have a command.@{par}

The first three rules are checked when you try to save or test a menu
definition. The last two are checked when you try to load a menu
definition, or select OK or Test in the @{"Edit Menu Definition" link EditWinNode}
window.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node TooltypesNode "ScreenMenuEd: Tooltypes and Shell Arguments"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Tooltypes and Shell Arguments@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=============================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

The tooltypes ScreenMenuEd looks for in its program icon are described
below. The arguments used from a Shell are identical, except where
stated otherwise. The full Shell template (with abbreviations) is:@{par}

@{code}
@{i}BGUI:@{ui}
             MF=MENUFILE, PS=PUBSCREEN/K, GN=GUIDENAME/K,
           LA=LANGUAGE/K, PI=PROJICON/K, NW=NOWARNCHANGE/S,
                  WF=WINDOWFONT/K, SW=SAVEWINSIZE/S

@{i}MUI:@{ui}
             MF=MENUFILE, PS=PUBSCREEN/K, GN=GUIDENAME/K,
           LA=LANGUAGE/K, PI=PROJICON/K, NW=NOWARNCHANGE/S
@{body}

ScreenMenuEd's tooltypes consist of two kinds:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{b}String@{ub} - You must supply a string of some kind; a filename,
public screen name, etc. For example, "LANGUAGE=deutsch".@{par}

@{b}Boolean@{ub} - In tooltypes you must supply one of the following: YES, NO,
TRUE or FALSE. For example, "NOWARNCHANGE=YES". You can also omit the
value entirely, which indicates the YES or TRUE state. On a Shell
command line, just state the keyword without a value to get the TRUE
state, omit the keyword for FALSE.@{par}
@{lindent 0}

@{code}
@{i}BGUI and MUI:@{ui}

    Tooltype         Type     Short Description
    ------------     ----     --------------------------------------
    @{"MENUFILE    " link MENUFILENode    }     STR      Menu file to load (Shell only).
    @{"PUBSCREEN   " link PUBSCREENNode   }     STR      Name of public screen to open on.
    @{"GUIDENAME   " link GUIDENAMENode   }     STR      Where to find ScreenMenuEd.guide.
    @{"LANGUAGE    " link LANGUAGENode    }     STR      Specify language catalog.
    @{"PROJICON    " link PROJICONNode    }     STR      Project icon for menu definition files.
    @{"NOWARNCHANGE" link NOWARNCHANGENode}     BOOL     Suppress change warning on exit.

@{i}BGUI only:@{ui}

    Tooltype         Type     Short Description
    ------------     ----     --------------------------------------
    @{"WINDOWFONT  " link WINDOWFONTNode  }     STR      Font to use in window.
    @{"SAVEWINSIZE " link SAVEWINSIZENode }     BOOL     Save window size/position on exit.
@{body}

In the MUI version, an option equivalent to WINDOWFONT can be set
using the MUI Preferences program, and SAVEWINSIZE isn't required as
MUI remembers window sizes automatically.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node MENUFILENode "ScreenMenuEd: MENUFILE Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}MENUFILE@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      String
Default:   <none>
Shell:     MF=MENUFILE
Tooltype:  <not applicable>
@{body}

This keyword, which is only usable from a Shell, lets you specify a
menu definition file that ScreenMenuEd should load initially. If you
don't specify a file, the program simply starts out with an empty,
unnamed menu definition.@{par}

From Workbench, you can specify an initial menu definition file to
load by shift-selecting a project icon in the standard manner, or by
setting a project icon's default tool to ScreenMenuEd and double
clicking on that.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node PUBSCREENNode "ScreenMenuEd: PUBSCREEN Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}PUBSCREEN@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      String
Default:   <system default>
Shell:     PS=PUBSCREEN/K
Tooltype:  PUBSCREEN
@{body}

The name of the public screen that ScreenMenuEd should initially open
its window on. If omitted, ScreenMenuEd opens on the default public
screen, which is normally Workbench, or in the case of the MUI
version, on the screen specified using the MUI Preferences program. Be
aware that public screen names are case-sensitive, ie. "MyScreen" is
not the same as "MYSCREEN".@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node GUIDENAMENode "ScreenMenuEd: GUIDENAME Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}GUIDENAME@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      String
Default:   ScreenMenuEd.guide
Shell:     GN=GUIDENAME/K
Tooltype:  GUIDENAME
@{body}

If ScreenMenuEd's guide is not on AmigaGuide's search path, set this
tooltype to the pathname of this guide so that on-line help is
available.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node LANGUAGENode "ScreenMenuEd: LANGUAGE Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}LANGUAGE@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      String
Default:   <system default>
Shell:     LA=LANGUAGE/K
Tooltype:  LANGUAGE
@{body}

ScreenMenuEd supports the locale library of AmigaOS 2.1 and above,
allowing it to display text and messages in your preferred language.
You would normally specify the language with the Locale Preferences
program; this tooltype allows you to override that setting if
necessary.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node PROJICONNode "ScreenMenuEd: PROJICON Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}PROJICON@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      String
Default:   def_ScreenMenuEd
Shell:     PI=PROJICON/K
Tooltype:  PROJICON
@{body}

Use this tooltype to tell ScreenMenuEd what project icon to use when
saving menu definition files. If the default tool of this icon is
blank, ScreenMenuEd will set it to "ScreenMenuEd" for all icons it
saves.@{par}

If you set PROJICON to the special value "NONE", no project icon will
be saved with menu definition files.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node NOWARNCHANGENode "ScreenMenuEd: NOWARNCHANGE Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}NOWARNCHANGE@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      Boolean
Default:   FALSE
Shell:     NW=NOWARNCHANGE/S
Tooltype:  NOWARNCHANGE
@{body}

Normally when you try to exit ScreenMenuEd having edited the current
menu definition, it asks for confirmation first, as you will lose the
changes that have been made but not saved. By setting NOWARNCHANGE to
TRUE, you can suppress this warning, if you wish.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node WINDOWFONTNode "ScreenMenuEd: WINDOWFONT Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}WINDOWFONT@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}==========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI only
Type:      String
Default:   <screen default>
Shell:     WF=WINDOWFONT/K
Tooltype:  WINDOWFONT
@{body}

ScreenMenuEd normally uses the default font of the screen it opens on.
If you wish to override this setting, specify the font with this
tooltype, using the following format: "example.font/12", where the 12
indicates the desired point size.@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} The "Fonts" page in the MUI Preferences program provides a
facility similar to this option.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node SAVEWINSIZENode "ScreenMenuEd: SAVEWINSIZE Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}SAVEWINSIZE@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI only
Type:      Boolean
Default:   FALSE
Shell:     SW=SAVEWINSIZE/S
Tooltype:  SAVEWINSIZE
@{body}

ScreenMenuEd normally opens its window centred under the mouse pointer
If, however, you would like the window to open with a particular size
and position each time, set the SAVEWINSIZE tooltype to TRUE.@{par}

This will cause ScreenMenuEd to save the window co-ordinates to a
small file called "ScreenMenuEd.win" in the ENV: directory each time
the program quits. Every time you start ScreenMenuEd, it will read and
re-use this window definition.@{par}

Once you have positioned the window as you like it, quit ScreenMenuEd,
unset the SAVEWINSIZE tooltype, and copy the "ScreenMenuEd.win" file
from ENV: to ENVARC:. It will then be copied back to ENV: by the
standard Startup-Sequence each time you boot your Amiga.@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} The MUI system automatically remembers the window's size and
position.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

